H1> Recovery scenarios

P> Things break sometimes. This page covers the three most common emergencies: corrupt core, forgotten admin password, and a site that became unreachable after installing a theme or plugin.

WARN> Always back up the database (and ideally the filesystem) [b]before[/b] applying any of the steps below. Recovery is much easier when you have a known-good snapshot.

H1> The site shows MySQL errors after a change

Q> I made some changes to my site and now I'm getting MySQL errors and my site doesn't appear.
A> Your core may have become corrupt. Reset it by visiting `http://yoursite.com/e107_files/resetcore/resetcore.php`. Always export a backup from [b]Admin → Database[/b] before applying changes; if something goes wrong you can then restore that backup from the same `resetcore.php` page.

H1> Lost main admin password

Q> I forgot my main admin password and now I can't access my admin area.
A> For security reasons there is no in-app password reset for an admin who is not logged in. Reset it manually with phpMyAdmin (or any MySQL client):

STEP> Open the `users` table.
STEP> Locate user #1 (the main admin) and edit it.
STEP> Change `user_password` to `4cb9c8a8048fd02294477fcb1a41191a` (this hash means [b]changeme[/b]).
STEP> Log in with the password [b]changeme[/b].
STEP> Open [b]User Settings[/b] and change the password to a strong, unique value [b]immediately[/b].

WARN> Do not leave the temporary `changeme` password in place. Anyone who reads this help file knows it.

H1> Site unreachable after installing a theme or plugin

Q> I installed a theme/plugin and now my site is unreachable – what can I do?
A> Use `resetcore.php` (see above) to restore the previous core configuration, or rename the offending plugin/theme folder via FTP/SSH so e107 stops loading it.

TIP> When testing a new theme, always click [b]Preview[/b] first instead of [b]Activate[/b] – the preview is sandboxed and cannot lock you out.
